    # ── SAMPLE ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
    narr:Sample_WorksFromWhatWasSaid_20260610
      a narr:Sample ;
      dct:title "Works from what was already said, and the question-first deck" ;
      dct:created "2026-06-10"^^xsd:date ;
      dct:description "Part 5 of the consulting-engagement session record (June 10-12, 2026). Scarlet Dame working session with Claude. Covers the 'works from what was already said' distinction (AI division of labor, objection pre-empt for executive AI fear) and the question-first iA Presenter deck design with operating rules." ;
      narr:inputLength 2847 .

    # ── NARRATIVE 1: Works from what was already said ───────────
    narr:Narrative_WorksFromWhatWasSaid

      dct:source narr:Sample_WorksFromWhatWasSaid_20260610 ;
      skos:broader narr:PositioningThesis ;
      skos:prefLabel "The AI Speaks to, References, and Works from What Was Already Said" ;
      skos:note "The goal is not to create an AI that makes new decisions in place of the decision-maker or process — it speaks to, references, and works from what was already said. 'What was said' deliberately exceeds 'what was decided': notions, open arguments, and half-formed positions steer thinking too, which is what conviction levels exist to carry. This is the objection pre-empt for executive AI fear and compresses to the existing tagline: Cited by AI." ;
      narr:theme "The AI's role is transmission and application of the record with citations — new judgment stays human; 'what was said' is broader than 'what was decided' because notions and open arguments steer thinking too" .

    # ── NARRATIVE 2: Question-first deck ────────────────────────
    narr:Narrative_QuestionFirstDeck

      dct:source narr:Sample_WorksFromWhatWasSaid_20260610 ;
      skos:broader narr:SalesDecks ;
      skos:prefLabel "The Question-First iA Presenter Deck" ;
      skos:note "A question-first iA Presenter deck designed in the session and saved to docs/sales/decks. Cover question, optional why-now beat for AI-native buyers only, three discovery questions as slides one through three, bridge (the judgment that fixes all three already exists; it's spoken in your meetings every week; then it evaporates), turn slide mirroring the three questions and closing with the distinction in Scarlet's own phrasing, engagement slide, example metrics, and close: 'Next call, I'll show you this conversation — turned into the beginning of your perspective.' Replaces a fill-in-the-blank metrics slide Scarlet rejected as gimmicky." ;
      narr:theme "The question-first deck does not present capabilities until the prospect has answered three pain questions about their own organization — the January pain-first deck decision taken to its limit" .

    # ── CLAIM 1: What was said exceeds what was decided ─────────
    narr:Claim_WhatWasSaidExceedsWhatWasDecided
      a narr:Claim ;
      dct:source narr:Sample_WorksFromWhatWasSaid_20260610 ;
      skos:note "'What was said' deliberately exceeds 'what was decided' because it is not just decisions — notions, open arguments, and half-formed positions steer thinking too. This is what conviction levels exist to carry. The distinction is the objection pre-empt for executive AI fear: the machine transmits and applies the record with citations; new judgment stays human — the client's, and Scarlet's in the calibration sessions." ;
      narr:aboutNode narr:Narrative_WorksFromWhatWasSaid ;
      narr:hasConvictionLevel narr:Conviction_Foundation ;
      narr:supports narr:Narrative_WorksFromWhatWasSaid .

    # ── CLAIM 2: Question-first deck structure ───────────────────
    narr:Claim_QuestionFirstDeckStructure
      a narr:Claim ;
      dct:source narr:Sample_WorksFromWhatWasSaid_20260610 ;
      skos:note "Deck structure: (1) Cover question; (2) Optional why-now beat for AI-native buyers only; (3) Three discovery questions as slides 1-3; (4) Bridge — the judgment that fixes all three already exists, it's spoken in your meetings every week, then it evaporates; (5) Turn slide mirroring the three questions, closing with the distinction in Scarlet's own phrasing: 'It doesn't decide for you. It speaks to, references, and works from what was already said.'; (6) Engagement slide; (7) Example metrics (replacing the fill-in-the-blank metrics slide Scarlet rejected as gimmicky — 'Provide examples'); (8) Close: 'Next call, I'll show you this conversation — turned into the beginning of your perspective.'" ;
      narr:aboutNode narr:Narrative_QuestionFirstDeck ;
      narr:hasConvictionLevel narr:Conviction_Foundation ;
      narr:supports narr:Narrative_QuestionFirstDeck .

    # ── CLAIM 3: Deck operating rules ───────────────────────────
    narr:Claim_DeckOperatingRules
      a narr:Claim ;
      dct:source narr:Sample_WorksFromWhatWasSaid_20260610 ;
      skos:note "Operating rules baked into the deck: (1) Consent beat spoken at the top of the call — 'I record my calls and build from them — you'll see exactly what that means by the end'; (2) Price structure appears on the slide but the number is spoken, never printed, until friendlies validate it; (3) No case-study slides — the close is the case study, performed on the prospect; (4) Show, don't send — call two is scheduled in the room. Consistent with the March 2026 podcast/interview sales-motion insight that the interview is simultaneously the sales call, the demo, and the onboarding." ;
      narr:aboutNode narr:Narrative_QuestionFirstDeck ;
      narr:hasConvictionLevel narr:Conviction_Foundation ;
      narr:supports narr:Narrative_SalesAsDelivery .

    # ── CLAIM 4: Pain-first deck taken to its limit ──────────────
    narr:Claim_PainFirstDeckTakenToLimit
      a narr:Claim ;
      dct:source narr:Sample_WorksFromWhatWasSaid_20260610 ;
      skos:note "The question-first design is the January pain-first deck decision taken to its limit: the deck does not present capabilities at all until the prospect has answered the three pain questions about their own organization." ;
      narr:aboutNode narr:Narrative_QuestionFirstDeck ;
      narr:hasConvictionLevel narr:Conviction_Boulder ;
      narr:supports narr:Narrative_FiveQuestionDiscoveryFramework .

    # ── STYLE OBSERVATION 1: Conversational distinction phrasing ─
    narr:StyleObs_ConversationalDistinction
      a narr:StyleObservation ;
      skos:broader narr:IdiolectPhrasing ;
